5000|$|Smith opposes {{austerity}} and {{has been}} strongly critical of Chancellor George Osborne's plan of public spending cuts. In May 2010, he apologised for an online article in which he compared the coalition government's austerity programme to domestic violence. As Shadow Work and Pensions Secretary, Smith attacked the government's <b>welfare</b> <b>reforms,</b> calling the bedroom tax [...] "unlawful and discriminatory". He followed the party whip by abstaining on the <b>Welfare</b> <b>Reform</b> and Work <b>bill</b> at its second reading on 20 July 2015, after voting for an amendment that set out the party's objections to aspects of it. On 27 October, Smith followed the party whip by voting against the bill at its third reading.|$|R
