5000|$|One {{of these}} <b>reforms</b> was the <b>Welfare</b> <b>Reform</b> and Work <b>Bill,</b> {{supported}} by Iain Duncan Smith (Secretary of State for Work and Pensions) and the Conservative Party. Many people have criticised the bill, with some even going {{as far as}} to defining it as a [...] "Pandora's box for Britain's poorest families". The cuts to tax credits have been criticised for unfairly disadvantaging the working poor, and a clause in the bill allows the benefits cap of Â£20,000 (Â£23,000 in London) to be reduced further, without any consultation with Parliament, thus making those from larger families even worse off. It also called for Â£12bn to be made in cuts, in accordance with the government's policy of austerity.|$|R
